IDEATION STAGES:
We were inspired by a gun and first person shooters, specifically aim trainer games like aim-labs.We wanted to use it to see if we could either have a memory 
aiming game or a game that keeps a score of the amounts of lights hit by the gun 
THE INITIAL IDEA
We initially decided that we would have a stepper motor smoothly move the gun along it's 4 electromagnetised coils at spacings of 30 degrees , with the left side being controlled by a push button and the right side also being controlled by a push button. this motor would have a gun as well as an ultrasound sensor attached to it which would detect objects i.e. an LED if it was blinking set at different distances around it.and the neopixel would light up when the game had to start. 
LOGIC FLOW (INITIAL IDEA)
F5 to run code 
neopixel starts turning red 4 at a time with time delay and buzzer sound and then when the game starts all 16 turn green
after that the 5 LEDs blink randomly and the goal is try to aim and shoot as many of the blinking leds as possible using the left and right movements of the push button 
to move the motor.

BEING OVERAMBITIOUS and pitfalls:
Our first mistake was trying to make it work with a stepper motor instead of a servo motor, as controlled angle movement could only be achieved by that and we 
did not want smooth movement 
as it had to be controlled by the Left and Right push buttons. 
even while trying to calibrate the servo motor, the first mistake we made was putting it into an outer while true loop , which was changed to a single while loop. 
we also tried to do some rough estimates for the ultrasound sensor which would move with the motor.
after that we troubleshooted the code more.I realised another issue, initialising the counter was a mistake we made. Not knowing how to properly define functions with arguments hindered a lot of scope for fixing and 
experimenting.

POST RESEARCH INSIGHTS:
Learning to define functions with proper arguments helped a lot. Using the modulo operator also was useful in the code, solved issues we were unable to debug otherwise
such as the constant rotation over the same angle unless the button was pressed twice.DESPITE this we still couldnt get both right and left to work , only right worked. 

